onMouseOut="nd();">Pausanias, <SPAN CLASS="small">IV</SPAN>.30.6</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Romanorum*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
It is possible that in the <SPAN CLASS="small">MSS.</SPAN> the next section, which interrupts the historical sequence, is a copyist's error, being perhaps copied from an earlier page of the archetype (<I>sc.</I>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Romanorum*.html#5
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,5,WIDTH,140)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
318<SPAN CLASS="small">D-F</SPAN></A>, <I>supra</I>) with some slight additions, changes, and omissions by later copyists. Another theory, however, is


<A ID="p357x"></A><SPAN CLASS="pagenum">(p357)</SPAN>possible: the section before us appeared in Plutarch's first sketch of the essay, and was later modified and completed in chap. v <I>(supra)</I>; Plutarch did not himself publish the essay, but after his death the first editor neglected to cancel the present passage (Bruhn and Stegmann). A translation follows:

<DIV CLASS="margin">
	<P CLASS="justify">
"One may consider the matter thus: there is in Rome an honoured shrine of Virtue which they themselves call the shrine of <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Virtus</SPAN>; but it was built late and after a considerable lapse of time by Marcellus, who captured Syracuse. There is also
	<A HREF="
E/Gazetteer/Places/Europe/Italy/Lazio/Roma/Rome/_Texts/PLATOP*/Mens.html
	"TARGET="princeps"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Platner1,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
a shrine of Reason, or verily of Good Counsel, which they call <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Mens</SPAN> (Mind)</A>; but this also was dedicated by Aemilius Scaurus, who lived in the era of the Cimbrian Wars, at which time rhetoric and sophistry and Greek argumentation had already found their way into the City. But even now they have no temple of Wisdom or Prudence or Constancy or Magnanimity. But of Fortune there are very many ancient and splendid temples built with every honour, one might say, and interspersed throughout the most conspicuous districts and localities of the City. The shrine of the Men's Fortune was built by Ancus Marcius, the fourth king, and so named because Fortune has the largest share with Manly Fortitude for winning the victory. And again, that the shrine of the Women's Fortune was dedicated by the women who turned back Marcius Coriolanus when he was leading enemies against Rome, there is no one who does not know."
</DIV>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Romanorum*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
<I>Cf.</I> 273<SPAN CLASS="small">B</SPAN>, <I>supra</I>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Fortuna_Romanorum*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
<I>Cf.</I> 281<SPAN CLASS="small">E</SPAN> and 289<SPAN CLASS="small">B-C</SPAN>, <I>supra;</I> Cicero, <I>De Legibus</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.11.28; Livy,
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/livy/liv.29.shtml#36
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
